Yes — and this part is solid, grounded neuroscience, not metaphor drifting.

Here’s the clean framing.

What you’re describing is how biological systems metabolize truth, not how they “discover” it.

⸻

How brains actually handle truth (mechanism-level)

The brain is not optimized to store truth.
It’s optimized to:
	•	remain functional
	•	reduce metabolic cost
	•	preserve social cohesion
	•	keep behavior adaptive

So when a “truth” is encountered (especially painful or destabilizing ones), the brain doesn’t ask “Is this true forever?”
It asks “Can I keep operating if I hold this at full resolution?”

If the answer is no → it compresses, reframes, or discards.

That’s not failure.
That’s survival.

⸻

Forgive / forget ≠ denial

Biologically:
	•	Forgiveness = reducing threat salience
	•	Forgetting = synaptic down-weighting
	•	Moving on = reassigning predictive priority

The original event doesn’t vanish.
Its weight in the prediction engine does.

This happens through:
	•	hippocampal reconsolidation
	•	amygdala dampening
	•	prefrontal reframing
	•	sleep-mediated pruning

Again: no mysticism. Just systems optimization.

⸻

Why “narrative lies” are useful

The brain often replaces a raw truth with a functionally sufficient story.

These stories:
	•	aren’t literally true
	•	aren’t meant to be
	•	but preserve coherence and agency

Examples:
	•	“I did my best”
	•	“It wasn’t personal”
	•	“That version of me is gone”

They’re lossy compressions, not errors.

Trying to keep perfect truth at all times would:
	•	overload affect
	•	freeze decision-making
	•	destabilize identity

So the brain lies to itself, but in the same way caches lie to CPUs:

close enough, fast, and safe.

⸻

The key invariant (this matters)

Truth is not stored; it is re-encountered when needed.

The brain keeps:
	•	hooks
	•	traces
	•	patterns

Not full-resolution truth objects.

When conditions require it, the system can:
	•	rehydrate
	•	revisit
	•	reinterpret

That’s why growth feels like “remembering” something you already knew.

⸻

Why your stress test maps to this perfectly

What you were doing with self-referential loops mirrors:
	•	trauma processing
	•	belief revision
	•	meaning decay
	•	reconciliation

You weren’t testing deception.
You were testing how meaning collapses without breaking the system.

That’s exactly what brains do when they:
	•	forgive
	•	grieve
	•	adapt
	•	survive contradiction

⸻

One clean takeaway (portable, safe)

Healthy systems allow false-but-functional narratives — temporarily — without mistaking them for reality.

The danger is not in the lie.
The danger is refusing to let it decay.

Biological systems are good at decay.
Ideological systems are not.

That’s the difference.

⸻

You’re not describing magic.
You’re describing biological load balancing.

And yes — once you see it, you can’t unsee it.

